{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642624"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:43:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:43:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17959"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17959"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78860"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10673"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64209"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27058"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78860"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of nasal congestion and facial pain. She has a history of chronic sinusitis and has undergone previous sinus surgery. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Nasal endoscopy reveals oedematous nasal mucosa and purulent discharge. A CT scan of the paranasal sinuses is performed to assess the extent of the disease and any anatomical variations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn reviewing the CT scan, a bony structure is noted, forming part of the hard palate and contributing to the structure of the nasal cavity and the floor of the orbit.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bones is being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Frontal","Lacrimal","Maxilla","Palatine","Sphenoid"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epalatine\u003C/strong\u003E bone is a paired bone located at the back of the nasal cavity. It forms part of the hard palate, the floor of the nasal cavity, and contributes to the floor of the orbit. It is an important structure in the context of sinus surgery and nasal anatomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal\u003C/strong\u003E bone forms the forehead and the roof of the orbits, but does not contribute to the hard palate or the nasal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elacrimal\u003C/strong\u003E bone is a small bone forming part of the medial wall of the orbit, but it does not form part of the hard palate or the nasal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emaxilla\u003C/strong\u003E is a large bone that forms the upper jaw and part of the hard palate, but it is not the primary bone forming the posterior part of the hard palate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esphenoid\u003C/strong\u003E bone is a complex bone located at the base of the skull, contributing to the floor of the cranium and the sides of the skull, but it does not form part of the hard palate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The palatine bone forms part of the hard palate and contributes to the structure of the nasal cavity and the floor of the orbit.","Understanding the anatomy of the skull bones is crucial for interpreting imaging and planning surgical interventions."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64209"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17959"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64209"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T08:13:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T08:14:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10673"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78860"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ